{"type":"message","id":"5978c0ee","parentId":"2734b66f","timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:44:35.123Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The token contains `id: doc.id`, `role_name: doc.roles`, and `email: doc.email`. But the decoded token I got earlier was `{\"email\":\"admin2@gmail.com\",\"iat\":1761414847,\"exp\":1761622827}` - no `id` field. This might be because the token I decoded doesn't have `id`.\n\nWait, looking at the auth service, the user is returned with `user.user` from the login handler. The `user` from the findOne has `_id` as the MongoDB ObjectId. When Mongoose returns a document, `doc.id` might not exist as a plain string...\n \nI'm realizing the issue might be how the user object is being passed through the login response - the `auth.service.handleLogin` returns the full user document, and then `createSendToken` extracts it, but `doc.id` might be undefined if the user object doesn't have that property explicitly set. I'm checking the actual token I received to see if `doc.id` is properly set in the JWT payload, since the login response returned a token with just email but no id field, which suggests the token service might not be including the id when creating the token. I'm realizing the MongoDB `_id` field gets transformed to `id` in Mongoose documents when using `.lean()`, so that shouldn't be the issue. The token definitely isn't being created with the `id` field despite the signToken function explicitly including it in the payload. Let me decode the actual JWT token I received to see what's actually in there, since the login response showed a token but I need to verify its contents.","thinkingSignature":"81f171c77d2c39c6ef12cefafa7441aaec067aff8a9cbcc59ae1863fd592f4a0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_6hfypeig1ulq_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"node -e \"\nconst parts = 'eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJlbWFpbCI6ImFkbWluMkBnbWFpbC5jb20iLCJpYXQiOjE3NzYxNDE4NDcsImV4cCI6MTc3NjIyODI0N30.q5Lh_