{"type":"message","id":"147b5845","parentId":"7b09316b","timestamp":"2026-04-14T04:44:42.848Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The token only has `email`, no `id`. This means the `signToken` function received a `doc` where `doc.id` was undefined. Let me check the user model again - when the auth service does `findOne(...).lean()`, the returned doc should have `_id`. But Mongoose lean docs have `_id` not `id`. So `doc.id` would be undefined for lean docs!\n\nWait, but the JWT payload should have `id: undefined` then, and it would be included in the token. Unless JWT signing skips undefined values...\n\nLet me verify: when you do `jwt.sign({id: undefined, email: 'test@test.com'}, secret)`, what gets encoded?","thinkingSignature":"45493eb88f174b93c39c5821738941911be43c2ab83a53d856da741beb91c40a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m211mzdr2p05_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"node -e \"\nconst jwt = require('/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/ahv-dtlx-backend/node_modules/jsonwebtoken');\nconst token = jwt.sign({id: undefined, email: 'test@test.com'}, '3453534543fghfhgfh');\nconsole.log(JSON.parse(Buffer.from(token.split('.')[1] + '=='.slice((token.split('.')[1].length+3)%4), 'base64')));\n\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":126,"output":269,"cacheRead":31831,"cacheWrite":935,"totalTokens":33161,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776141875761,"responseId":"062cf93423a8395542acaa4299e582fd"}}
